SoulSupport is a mobile mental health platform built to bridge the gap between individuals and professional care — 
making support accessible, personalized, and human.

Designer's reflection:

This project taught me that designing for mental health is fundamentally an act of trust architecture. 
Every decision — from the warmth of a color to the phrasing of an error message — 
either builds or erodes the user's willingness to be vulnerable.

The most significant tension we navigated was between clinical credibility and emotional warmth. 
Too sterile and users feel surveilled. Too casual and they don't trust the medical validity. Finding that middle path — 
a product that feels like a conversation with a wise, caring friend who also happens to be a professional — is the core design challenge of mental health UX.

If I were to extend this project, the next frontier is crisis detection — 
using AI to identify linguistic patterns in chat that signal acute distress, and surfacing emergency resources proactively rather than waiting for a user to ask.
